commentBody:
That took a while. I enjoyed the well executed theme, but unfortunately, I:
- have never heard of SAWEETIE, BIALY, TIG, MRSWHO, or either of the referenced LIAM or LANA;
- couldn't remember how to spell CONNOISEURS or AENEAS;
- took a long time to remember AVOCETS 
- had to guess YES from the crosses; 
- was def not a fan of DMED/IMED, SNOT or HAP.

On top of that, I think the clues for CAPE and ITCHY are pretty weak. 
The pilgrims landed at A cape (CAPE Cod), but not at "CAPE". 
And while some rashes are accompanied by an itch, and some itches are accompanied by a rash, "Feeling rash?" just doesn't work for me.

@Sam Lyons

I thought of you when I saw clues and answers referring to Aeneas, Dante's "Inferno," and Joyce's "Ulysses." 

And I agree this was a fun puzzle.

@Barry A.

Barry, I’m sending a smile your way just to see if it goes through. The other day, I tried to reply to you three times, but couldn’t get out of Emu Stalag IV. 

@Eric H. 

It was “sweet [puzzle fill], the banquet of the mind.”

@Steve L

Like Matthew O, I started with BLueS at 96D, only to have the Alou brothers set me straight.

I hadn't realized that Alou was their mother's surname. I too wonder how crossword-famous they would be if baseball fans knew them as the Castros.

@Barry

Succinct, brief, to the point, to a fault.

But I have no idea what you're saying.

@Marc Schmied

Ok, thanks, but is there a functional difference?  

Do I do one thing with one app and the other with a different app?

@Francis

You may not recognize Maya Lin's name, but I'll bet you have seen (at least in photos) her best-known work, the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, D.C. It's pretty impressive that she was a 21-year-old architecture student when she won the design competition.

<a href="https://youtu.be/mL9rrCJkBJs?si=62hk2tnJ-ohwFGP6" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/mL9rrCJkBJs?si=62hk2tnJ-ohwFGP6</a>

@Francis

I figured you would recognize that memorial. 

I have a cousin whose husband Steve was killed in action shortly after he arrived in Vietnam. I visited the memorial about 10 years ago and found Steve’s name on it. (I was about seven or eight when he died, and I only vaguely remember him.)

@Barry Ancona
Maya Lin attended the same high school I did - Athens. As did Joe Burrow, Atul Gawande, and David Wilhelm.
For a smaller school in a rural(ish) setting, AHS has produced some distinguished alums - in no small part due to the fact that Athens is the home of Ohio University. "Harvard on the Hocking", as they call it.

@Eric Hougland
Way, way back in the late 1950's, when I was at the Univ. of Texas in Austin, we flocked to foreign movies, especially Italian, films that were blowing the lids off our heads.

Fellini is more approachable, but Monica Vitti was the star of "La Notte," "L'Avventura," "Red Desert," "L'Eclisse," and other films that would be (as Preston Sturges might have said) too deep dish for current audiences.  We loved them.

@Dutchiris

You're a UT alum? Both my RTF and law degrees are from UT.

UT continued to have programs with a lot of foreign films into the 1970s. I assume they still do, but it's been 20+ years since I've seen a movie on campus.

@Eric Hougland

Not a graduate. Dropped out so that my then-husband and I (both undergrads) could stop starving (I was down to 97 lbs and tall ).  An English Dept Prof suggested I apply for a job in the UT Library (I didn't know at the time that he was Chair of the Library Board), where I worked first in the library reference dept, later  in rare books cataloguing. (I majored in English Lit, not Library Sci.)

Happy days, but itchy feet, and after a few years, I moved on.

@Grumpy

Do yourself a favor: discover LANA Del Rey. She's an incredible artist.

I know how to spell CONNOISSEUR in English because I specifically spent time to learn it, once. In Polish it's written down phonetically and much more simply as "koneser".

@Andrzej

There are two kinds of people in the world:  

Those who think puns are the highest form of humor, and those who think it is the lowest form of humor.

@Eric Hougland

If you do decide to visit, we will have to get in touch. I could give you and your husband a tour of some very Warsaw-y places most tourists probably never see.

@Oikofuge

You phrased that much better than I could ever have. Thank you.

@Larry

See noun definition 4: “something difficult to do or deal with”
<a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/bear" target="_blank">https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/bear</a>

@Alex

Most bagel shops, at least in the NY area, also sell BIALYS. BIALYS always have onions in the center and poppy seeds sprinkled on top. They differ from bagels in two main ways: they’re not boiled before baking, like bagels are, and they have a depression in the center, not a hole. 

The word is pronounced bee-AH-lee in English.

@BT
The three brothers ALOU are famed for their talent as MLB players (Cincinnati Reds!) so it i definitely Americana, but surely there are many lumberjacks elsewhere (Canada, of course, but I recall crews working in the Schwartzwald --before the environmental disaster really hit)...  

I know the word BIALY but not actually what it is  (just "something to eat, from the deli")  ....Russian?  Yiddish? Term?

@LBG

Joe PESCI is a wonderful actor (as you might know).

If “Home Alone” isn’t your type of movie (I saw it once years ago and have no desire to see it again), maybe something like “GoodFellas” or “My Cousin Vinny” is of more interest to you.

@JohnWM

That's great! And just as catchy as (and more appropriate than) the other song I was thinking of. Though it also fits 96A...

<a href="https://youtu.be/FshU58nI0Ts?si=f6D_8-2gnL7Ek2SM" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/FshU58nI0Ts?si=f6D_8-2gnL7Ek2SM</a>

@Grant

RADIOHEAD and INXS were easy. URIAH Heep was easy too, and still would have been had the clue referred to the band. Maidenhair FERNS was a gimme.

Wasn’t so much that the many proper names were obscure, but just that there seemed to be so many. I suppose I’m simply more fond of puzzles that include a lot of interesting *words*.

@Grant
Even before that, Uriah Heep was in David Copperfield…you know, Charles Dickens?
I’d never heard of the band before  ;)

@Chet,

Woohoo! That’s a heck of a streak! Congratulations!! 🍾🎉 

(I’m about two weeks behind you 😊)

@Beth

DOM, in this context, is short for Latin dominus, "lord". It's a term of respect for some senior ranks in some Roman Catholic monastic institutions. 
Notably, among the Benedictines, which was Dom Pérignon's order.

